93 Victoria State of Origin players}}\n{{1994 Victoria State of Origin players}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Langford, Chris}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:People educated at Melbourne Grammar School]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian rules footballers from Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Hawthorn Football Club players]]\n[[Category:All-Australians (1953\u20131988)]]\n[[Category:Victorian State of Origin players]]\n[[Category:Australian Football Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:All-Australians (AFL)]]\n[[Category:E. J. Whitten Medal winners]]\n[[Category:Australia international rules football team players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox AFL biography\n| name = Chris Langford\n| image = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1963|1|2|df=y}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| originalteam = [[Melbourne Grammar School|Melbourne Grammar]]\n| height = 193 cm\n| weight = 92 kg\n| position = \n| statsend = 1997\n| years1 = 1983\u20131997\n| club1 = [[Hawthorn Football Club|Hawthorn]]\n| games_goals1 = 303 (33)\n| careerhighlights = '''Club'''\n*4x [[Australian Football League|VFL/AFL]] Premiership: [[1986 VFL Grand Final|1986]], [[1988 VFL Grand Final|1988]], [[1989 VFL Grand Final|1989]], [[1991 AFL Grand Final|1991]]\n*4x All-Australian: 1987, 1988, 1989, 1994\n*3x VFL Team of Year: 1987, 1988, 1989\n*[[Australian Football Hall of Fame]]\n*[[Hawthorn Football Club|Hawthorn]] Hall of Fame\n*[[List of Hawthorn Football Club captains|Hawthorn captain]]: 1994\n\n'''Representative'''\n* [[E. J. Whitten Medal]]: 1987, 1993\n| fullname = \n}}\n'''Chris Langford''' (born 2 January 1963) is a former professional [[Australian rules football]]er who has been an [[AFL Commission]]er since 1999.\n\n==Player==\nLangford is best known for his 303-game career for the [[Hawthorn Football Club]] between 1983 and 1997.\n\nLangford played his early games for Hawthorn on the wing or as the second ruckman. He had a good leap which compensated for his lack of height. It was after the retirement of Peter Knights and David O'Halloran he switched to full back . It was that position in which he won his first All-Australian selection in 1987.\n\nA defender, Langford won four premierships with Hawthorn, in 1986, 1988, 1989 and 1991. He captained the club in the 1994 season and earned a second [[All-Australian]] selection.\n\nHe holds a place on the interchange bench in Hawthorn's official 'Team of the Century'.\n\nLate in his career, Langford moved to [[Sydney]] where he worked as an accountant, commuting to Melbourne to training and play with his club. In 2012, he moved back to Melbourne.\n\n===Merger game===\nLangford's antics at the end of the [[Melbourne Hawks|merger game]] against Melbourne in 1996 inspired many Hawthorn members to vote against the merger proposal. Langford (Hawthorn's full back) took off his Hawthorn jumper and proudly held it above his head while leaving the field. Langford was only one of the then playing list to display his disapproval of the plan.\n\n==Statistics==\n:<ref>[https://afltables.com/afl/stats/players/S/Stephen_Silvagni.html Stephen Silvagni's player profile at AFL Tables]</ref>\n\n{{AFL player statistics legend}}\n{{AFL player statistics start with votes}}\n|-\n|- style=\"background-color: #EAEAEA\"\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" | [[1983 VFL season|1983]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{AFL Haw}}\n| 28 || 11 || 3 || 9 || 105 || 66 || 171 || 39 || {{n/a}} || 0.3 || 0.8 || 9.5 || 6.0 || 15.5 || 3.5 || {{n/a}} || 0\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" | [[1984 VFL season|1984]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{AFL Haw}}\n| 28 || 22 || 17 || 19 || 185 || 62 || 247 || 54 || {{n/a}} || 0.8 || 0.9 || 8.4 || 2.8 || 11.2 || 2.5 || {{n/a}} || 1\n|- style=\"background-color: #EAEAEA\"\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" | [[1985 VFL season|1985]]\n|style=\"text-align: